<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/gre_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/treports/treports.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/gre_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Santa Rosa, CA 8.31.02 *1st Place!*<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10879'>Lisa "Celebrian" Gansky</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10879&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 5, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Earlier in the summer, I talked to my sister Linda briefly on the phone (she called to ask my parents for some money—figures!) and she mentioned that I never visited her (she lives up north in Rohnert Park, very close to Santa Rosa). I realized that I would have Labor Day off of work, so I let her know. I talked to T.J., who I’d lost to back in June in the Northern Cali Territorial (check out my tournament report for more on that beating), and he said he’d probably have a tournament going that weekend. Needless to say, that was enough to convince me! <br>
<br>
I let Linda know that I’d be coming to visit her and that I’d probably play in the tournament, and then invited Mike Mendoza along to come play in the tournament as well. The drive up wasn’t so bad. And the store was really close to my sister’s. There was a bit of traffic between Rohnert Park and Santa Rosa, but nothing too bad. We got there and said hi to everyone, T.J., Mason, etc. and hung out for a while waiting for some more people to show up before T.J. got the tournament started. I think there ended up being 12 players once Drew’s cousin and T.J. joined.<br>
<br>
Ahead of time, I’m sorry for the lack of details. Most of my games were pretty quick (accept for the game against Drew), so…well, read on, you’ll see.<br>
<br>
<br>
Game 1 vs. Drew Biederman (1577) a.k.a. Space-out Boy (Moria/Big Fellowship)<br>
<br>
T.J. had told me a bit about Drew beforehand when we were chatting on AIM. Apparently the kid has extreme difficulty focusing in anything, hence the nickname Space-out Boy. Once Drew sat down he started talking to me. Here’s how the conversation went:<br>
<br>
Drew: How long have you been playing?<br>
Me: Oh, since April. What about you?<br>
Drew (with a sly grin on his face): Since it came out.<br>
<br>
Anyways, I was playing my Nazgul/Horn deck that I played last week (with a few changes), so we bid. He bid two to my zero and opted to go first. The game went really slowly (See T.J.’s report for further details on this). He had 6 guys down and I played Enquea. He says, “What does that card do?” So I let him read it. “Oh,” he says. I took out Boromir (LOG), just cuz he’s a tank.<br>
<br>
It was about that time that a lady (T.J. since told me this was Drew’s aunt) came in the tournament room and proceeded to start talking to Drew during our game. He couldn’t get focused back on the game at all. I had to keep trying to get him to pay attention. It didn’t help that the lady wouldn’t leave either. She watched for a few minutes and Drew just couldn’t decide which was more important, playing or talking. T.J. came over and I asked him to be so kind as to not let the game time out. Luckily he told me that he wasn’t timing it, so that made me feel a little better. I wanted to ask the lady to leave, but I didn’t want to be rude. Honestly though I was a bit surprised she didn’t realize she was interrupting something. She didn’t even seem to notice I was there!<br>
<br>
So anyways, back to the game. At site 3 I pulled Rumil and Tale of Gil-galad, so I played that. That was pretty nice. Kept him from stacking anyone on swarms. He got one Troll on me the whole game, and that’s pretty much how it went. I ditched almost all the conditions he played (thank God for Secret Sentinels). I doubled from 6-8 and then won at 9, never really seeing a swarm. He was on site 6 when I won. He didn’t get to move very fast because my Nazis slowed him down. Overall, it was a relatively easy walk once Drew actually started playing. Changing it up to Aragorn RON has really helped my deck when facing Moria.<br>
<br>
FW +3/3<br>
<br>
Highs: Rumil with Gil-galad against Moria.<br>
Lows: Drew’s Aunt and Drew’s short attention span.<br>
<br>
<br>
Game 2 vs. Frank Pinkela (1708) a.k.a. Burden Lover (Archery/Sauron/Twilight Nazgul Corruption)<br>
<br>
After his first game I heard Frank bragging about his corruption deck—that he’d won every single game he’d played with it by corruption. So he’s the Burden Lover. We got down to it, and he won the bid and chose to go first (I bid zero most of the time, plus I already knew he was playing corruption, so why would I help him by adding burdens?). I drew up my hand and almost laughed. Brilliant shadow hand! Out of the corner of my eye, I saw him add Aragorn’s Bow to Aragorn. Even better, hehehe!<br>
<br>
When he moved to site two, Bree Streets, I just played two guys, Cantea and Toldea. He told me to take two archery, but I stopped him. “What about maneuvers Frank?” I dropped two Relentless Charges. Both Aragorn and Legolas died. On my turn I played a bunch of stuff. I was going to stop, but none of his guys survived, so I went on. D’oh, he wasn’t playing the Fords. I made it easily. At site 2 I also got rid of his Orc Bowmen (but forgot to snag Thin and Stretched since it was buried under Frodo) with my Secret Sentinels. I asked Frank if I could lose that too, but he said no. No worries though, I had another Sentinels in hand, and I used it at site 3 to get rid of Thin and Stretched and yet another Bowmen. When he hit site 3, I couldn’t play anything. His little Frodo lasted to site 4, Eregion Hills. I gatesed in Cantea and he was done.<br>
<br>
We had a lot of time left, so we played again. I didn’t get the double Relentless Charges, but I made it to site 9…….and got corrupted. Props for that Frank. I don’t think I’d ever lost by corruption before.<br>
<br>
FW +3/6<br>
<br>
Highs: Winning against Frank, cuz he was getting a little overconfident with his deck. Double Relentless Charges at site 2.<br>
Lows: None really.<br>
<br>
Frank and I traded a little after the game, then for the first time I actually realized that T.J. was playing. T.J. ended up paired against Mike, and I ended up going against Ethan, who doesn’t have a rating, but managed to give Mike a run for his money and beat someone else.<br>
<br>
<br>
Game 3 vs. Ethan Rustad (1500) a.k.a. The Cute Little Kid (Nazgul)<br>
This game was great for me because I got my entire Fellowship set up by site 3. His Nazgul couldn’t touch Boromir or Aragorn (strength 15 and 16 against Nazgul respectively). I didn’t even have to use the Horn. Every single time he threw down a Black Breath, I’d have a Sentinels in my hand to get rid of it. Cool stuff. I ended up winning at site 8, when he tried to double-move. Three Nazgul was too many for his beaten-up crew.<br>
<br>
FW +3/9<br>
<br>
Highs: Winning three straight and getting my fellowship set up right away.<br>
Lows: Ethan trying to trick me into telling him what was in my deck. He’s a cute kid…and he knows it! I bet a lot of people fall for that. :)<br>
<br>
Game 4 vs. Michael Mendoza (1873) a.k.a. The Master (Gandalf/Nazgul)<br>
Well, this was the showdown. Michael and I played 5-6 games before the tournament, and he beat me down every single time, so that’s why he’s also known as The Master. There was only one game that was remotely close, and that was when I doubled from 7-9 and ate it at 9…Each of those games we played I’d bid zero, and Mike made me go first, so I figured I should change it up and try to get him to go first. I bid one and so did he. He was shocked about that. We rolled dice and I won, 6 to his 4. Yup Mikey, you’re going first. :)<br>
<br>
I drew up my hand and to my surprise I had a Nazi, Breath, and Too Great and Terrible. Wonderful cards when your opponent starts Gandalf. He plays Aragorn and moves to the Streets. I play Toldea, play a Black Breath, and then play Too Great. Gandalf takes two for that, and then Aragorn takes two against Toldea and I breathed him. Mike stops. On my turn all I have to play are allies and support stuff. But I don’t want to give him too much pool because knowingly he has a handful of guys to drop on me, so instead, I hang onto Galadriel and Rumil. Details are hazy, but I’m pretty sure Boromir took two here. It’s kinda sad—I’ve played so many games against Mike that I’m trying to remember which scenarios happened in which game. :) I’m sure if I got anything really wrong, he’ll make a correction when he reviews this.<br>
<br>
At site three, I get down fierce Nelya and another guy to kill off both Gandalf and Aragorn. Wow. I have to admit that I took myself by surprise there. This is going rather well, wouldn’t you say? Mike stops, and it’s my turn to hit the Fords. I draw up Aragorn, so I play him, add two to heal Boromir (I pretty much don’t have a choice) and move. He gets down a squad, and initially I think I’m done, but then I realize I can assign a Nazgul to Frodo and exert Merry. On the fierce Boromir dies, Merry dies, and Aragorn ends up taking two. So I’m left with just tipped Frodo and Aragorn (it just sucks when Boromir dies at site 3 in a Horn Deck, doesn’t it???).<br>
<br>
So Mike moves to 4 and I can’t play anything. At site 4, he plays Twilight Nelya. Frodo and his burdens and Aragorn without Armor don’t like this at all. Aragorn dies. So it comes to the Bridge. Mike doesn’t draw anything, so poor little Frodo has to take on a ferocious Nazgul all by his lonesome, and that’s game. <br>
<br>
FW +3/12<br>
<br>
Highs: I can’t lie…it was good to finally beat Mike after getting beat down repeatedly (and badly) by him. Not to mention he’s been a mentor to me when it comes to Rings. All that play-testing really paid off—thanks for that Mike.<br>
Lows: Beating up and getting beaten up by a friend. He slapped my guys upside the head, that’s for sure. :) But I did it back...<br>
<br>
<br>
So that’s that. I won my second straight tournament. Who would have thought that would be possible? :) T.J. asked me what packs I preferred for prize support and I said I didn’t mind. Luckily he picked Realms and guess what I pull? Elrond, Herald to Gil-galad foil. Sweet card! I’m usually the one that gets Despair and Wealth of Moria in packs (not even the foil versions, just the regular ones).<br>
<br>
I did some trading, got some really cool stuff off T.J. and some others (even got a Lurtz foil!), and then we all headed out.<br>
<br>
Weekend Props:<br>
-T.J. for running a great tournament, for the sweet trades, and the most-excellent prize support.<br>
-Mike and my sis for letting me crash with them.<br>
-Mike for the play-testing.<br>
-The players up north for being a really cool, relaxed, and friendly bunch.<br>
-San Francisco water, air, and pretty much everything, but especially for not being L.A. It’s a beautiful city for sure. I won’t ever forget the way the Golden Gate Bridge looked coming back into the city. I’d even say it was worth the increased fee ($5 instead of $3).<br>
-Me for somehow managing to win my second straight tournament. :)<br>
<br>
Weekend Slops:<br>
-Drew’s aunt.<br>
-Traffic…there wasn’t too much on the way up, but my drive back to L.A. on Monday was HORRIBLE. Plus driving alone is never fun.<br>
-Rob Nen, cuz he blew that save…and he’s on my fantasy team. ERA of infinity isn’t good for anyone.<br>
-Podracing.<br>
-Rats for being nocturnal.<br>
-Bubble Boy...what a cheesy movie. It had some moments, but for the most part it was horrible. <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?id=3969&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
